I have a custom codec for a simple case class defined like this:
 
{code}
case class ID[T](id: Int) extends AnyVal
case class TestItem1(id: ID[TestItem1], name: Option[String])
case class TestItem2(id: ID[TestItem2], name: Option[String])

class IDCodec[T] extends Codec[ID[T]] {
  override def encode(writer: BsonWriter, value: ID[T], encoderContext: EncoderContext): Unit = writer.writeInt32(value.id)
  override def getEncoderClass: Class[ID[T]] = classOf[ID[T]]
  override def decode(reader: BsonReader, decoderContext: DecoderContext): ID[T] = ID[T](reader.readInt32())
}
{code} 

The codec can serialize the case class into "\{id: 1, name: "whatever}". If I comment out // extends AnyVal in the ID implementation, then it just works in both ways. But if ID extends AnyVal I get following exception:

{code}
org.scalatest.exceptions.GeneratorDrivenPropertyCheckFailedException: ClassCastException was thrown during property evaluation.
 Message: java.lang.Integer cannot be cast to my.namespace.TestRegistry$ID
 Occurred when passed generated values (
 arg0 = TestItem1(ID(1),Some())
)
{code}
 
Can be wrong, but I think it worked in 2.3.0. We held it back because of index creation error. Now 2.4.1 has another bug :)

The following simple test fails randomly that uses Observable.toFuture() fails randomly (at a rather low rate though). It seems related to a concurrency issue linked to the completed flag in SingleResultCallbackSubscription/AbstractSubscription:

{code:scala}package random.failure

import org.mongodb.scala.model.ReturnDocument.AFTER
import org.mongodb.scala.model.Updates.{inc, setOnInsert}
import org.mongodb.scala.model.{FindOneAndUpdateOptions, IndexOptions, Indexes, Filters => F}
import org.mongodb.scala.{Document, MongoClient}
import org.scalatest.{MustMatchers, WordSpecLike}

import scala.concurrent.ExecutionContext.Implicits.global
import scala.concurrent.duration._
import scala.concurrent.{Await, Future}

class RandomFailureTest extends WordSpecLike
                        with MustMatchers {

  "MongoBitcoinPaymentDAO" should {

    "generate unique address index" in {

      (0 until 10).foreach { _ =>
        val generatedAddressIndexes = Await.result(Future.sequence((1 to 500)
          .map(_ => update())), 10.seconds)
          .toSet

        generatedAddressIndexes.size mustBe 500
      }
    }
  }

  private val findCollection = {
    val db = MongoClient("mongodb://localhost:27017").getDatabase("database")
    val collection = db.getCollection[Document]("collection")
    for {
      _ <- collection.createIndex(Indexes.ascending("id"), IndexOptions().unique(true)).toFutureOption()
    } yield collection
  }.flatMap { collection =>
    collection
      .findOneAndUpdate(F.equal("id", "id"), setOnInsert("value", 0), FindOneAndUpdateOptions().upsert(true).returnDocument(AFTER))
      .toFuture()
      .map(_ => collection)
  }

  def update(): Future[Integer] = findCollection.flatMap(_
    .findOneAndUpdate(F.equal("id", "id"), inc("value", 1), FindOneAndUpdateOptions().upsert(true).returnDocument(AFTER))
    .toFuture()
    .map(_.getInteger("value")) // <- The exception is thrown here
  )
}
{code}

Indeed the result is either "Ok" or the following exception:

{code:java}java.lang.NullPointerException was thrown.
java.lang.NullPointerException
at org.mongodb.scala.package$.documentToUntypedDocument(package.scala:339)
at random.failure.RandomFailureTest.$anonfun$update$2(RandomFailureTest.scala:46)
at scala.util.Success.$anonfun$map$1(Try.scala:251)
at scala.util.Success.map(Try.scala:209)
at scala.concurrent.Future.$anonfun$map$1(Future.scala:288)
at scala.concurrent.impl.Promise.liftedTree1$1(Promise.scala:29)
at scala.concurrent.impl.Promise.$anonfun$transform$1(Promise.scala:29)
at scala.concurrent.impl.CallbackRunnable.run(Promise.scala:60)
at java.util.concurrent.ForkJoinTask$RunnableExecuteAction.exec(ForkJoinTask.java:1402)
at java.util.concurrent.ForkJoinTask.doExec(ForkJoinTask.java:289)
at java.util.concurrent.ForkJoinPool$WorkQueue.runTask(ForkJoinPool.java:1056)
at java.util.concurrent.ForkJoinPool.runWorker(ForkJoinPool.java:1692)
at java.util.concurrent.ForkJoinWorkerThread.run(ForkJoinWorkerThread.java:157)
{code}

The reason seems linked to the fact that SingleResultCallbackSubscription.requestInitialData() does a
{code:java}
...
                    synchronized (SingleResultCallbackSubscription.this) {
                        completed = true;
                    }
                    addToQueue(result);
...
{code}

and AbstractSubscription.processResultsQueue():
{code:java}
...
            while (true) {
                long localWanted;

                synchronized (this) {
                    ...
                    if (resultsQueue.isEmpty()) {
                        completed = checkCompleted();
                        ...
                        break;
                    }
                    ...
                }
                ...

                while (localWanted > 0) {
                    TResult item = resultsQueue.poll();
                    ...
                }
            }
...
{code}

So basically SingleResultCallbackSubscription set complete=true and then put the data in the queue which can in some rare concurrency cases make AbstractSubscription see completed flag before it has pulled the value from the queue although it's there.
More specifically, the scenario that causes the issue is
- Thread1 : resultsQueue.isEmpty() = true
- Thread2 : completed = true;
- Thread1 : completed = checkCompleted() ; which is true
- Thread2 : addToQueue(result); Too late

In other words it seems like the Observable to Future can fail at any time (or return randomly a None in toFutureOption) even though there is some data.
That also means that even with upsert=true and AFTER_DOCUMENT, we can get back a null which should not be possible...

I ran into this issue when working with an actual MongoDB Observable, but it's easy to reproduce just using in-memory Observables as well.

 

Running the following code will result in the future timing out (i.e. the observable never completing)
{code:java}
val observable = Observable(1 to 10)
val future = observable
  .filter(_ % 2 == 0)
  .flatMap(v => Observable(List(v)))
  .toFuture()

// This call will time out
println(Await.ready(future, 10.seconds)) {code}
Removing the {{filter}} call will resolve it (in that it will complete), but of course it means that no filtering will be done
{code:java}
 val observable = Observable(1 to 10)
    val future = observable
//      .filter(_ % 2 == 0)
      .flatMap(v => Observable(List(v)))
      .toFuture()

    // This works
    println(Await.ready(future, 10.seconds)) {code}
As mentioned above, this is also a problem when using an Observable based on a MongoDB find call for example.
